Chapter 4: Geometry of Multi‑Agent Correlations

4.1 Correlation Tensors and Agent Systems

Definition 4.1.1. An $n$-agent inference system consists of:

1. C*-algebras $\mathcal{A}_i$ (one per agent);
2. A joint state $\omega$ on $\mathcal{A}_1 \otimes_{\min} \cdots \otimes_{\min} \mathcal{A}_n$;
3. For each agent $i$, a set of measurement observables $\{A_i^{(k)}\} \subset \mathcal{A}_i$, usually projection‑valued measures.

Definition 4.1.2. The correlation tensor with respect to measurements $A_i$ is
C_{i_1 \ldots i_n} = \omega(A_{1}^{(i_1)} \otimes \cdots \otimes A_{n}^{(i_n)}).

4.2 Convex Geometry

Definition 4.2.1. For $\mathcal{A}_i = M_{d_i}(\mathbb{C})$, define:

· $\mathcal{C}_{\text{class}}$: correlations from states that are convex combinations of product states;
· $\mathcal{C}_{\text{quant}}$: correlations from arbitrary states on the tensor product;
· $\mathcal{C}_{\text{NS}}$: correlations satisfying no‑signalling constraints.

Theorem 4.2.2. $\mathcal{C}_{\text{class}} \subsetneq \mathcal{C}_{\text{quant}} \subsetneq \mathcal{C}_{\text{NS}}$ for $n\ge 2$, $d_i\ge 2$.

4.3 The Maakoul Constant

Definition 4.3.1 (Maakoul Constant). For an $n$-agent system with local algebras $\mathcal{A}_i$,
\mathfrak{M}(\mathcal{A}_1,\dots,\mathcal{A}_n) = \sup_{\beta \neq 0} \frac{B_{\text{quant}}(\beta)}{B_{\text{class}}(\beta)},


where $B_{\text{class}}(\beta) = \sup_{C\in\mathcal{C}_{\text{class}}} |\beta(C)|$, $B_{\text{quant}}(\beta) = \sup_{C\in\mathcal{C}_{\text{quant}}} |\beta(C)|$.

Theorem 4.3.2 (Grothendieck Equality). For $\mathcal{A}_1 = M_d(\mathbb{C})$, $\mathcal{A}_2 = M_d(\mathbb{C})$ ($d\ge 2$),
\mathfrak{M} = K_G,


where $K_G$ is the complex Grothendieck constant ($1.676... \le K_G \le 1.782...$). In particular, $\mathfrak{M} \ge \sqrt{2}$ from the CHSH inequality.

Proof. We prove both upper and lower bounds.

Upper bound. Any Bell functional $\beta$ can be written as $\beta(C) = \sum_{ij} \beta_{ij} C_{ij}$ for a complex matrix $\beta$. By Tsirelson’s theorem [Tsirelson, 1987], quantum correlations are exactly those of the form $C_{ij} = \langle u_i, v_j \rangle$ for unit vectors $u_i, v_j$ in some Hilbert space. Hence
B_{\text{quant}}(\beta) = \sup_{\|u_i\|,\|v_j\|\le 1} \Bigl|\sum_{ij} \beta_{ij} \langle u_i, v_j \rangle\Bigr|.


The classical value is $B_{\text{class}}(\beta) = \sup_{|a_i|,|b_j|\le 1} \bigl|\sum_{ij} \beta_{ij} a_i b_j\bigr|$. Grothendieck’s inequality [Grothendieck, 1953] states that there exists a constant $K_G$ such that for every matrix $\beta$,
\sup_{\|u_i\|,\|v_j\|\le 1} \Bigl|\sum_{ij} \beta_{ij} \langle u_i, v_j \rangle\Bigr| \le K_G \sup_{|a_i|,|b_j|\le 1} \Bigl|\sum_{ij} \beta_{ij} a_i b_j\Bigr|.


Thus $B_{\text{quant}}(\beta) \le K_G B_{\text{class}}(\beta)$ for all $\beta$, giving $\mathfrak{M} \le K_G$.

Lower bound. By definition of $K_G$ as the optimal constant in Grothendieck’s inequality, for any $\varepsilon > 0$ there exists a matrix $\beta$ such that
\sup_{\|u_i\|,\|v_j\|\le 1} \Bigl|\sum_{ij} \beta_{ij} \langle u_i, v_j \rangle\Bigr| > (K_G - \varepsilon) \sup_{|a_i|,|b_j|\le 1} \Bigl|\sum_{ij} \beta_{ij} a_i b_j\Bigr|.


The left‑hand side is exactly $B_{\text{quant}}(\beta)$ (the supremum is achieved because the unit spheres are compact in finite dimensions, and we can take $d$ large enough to approximate the Hilbert space). Hence $\mathfrak{M} \ge K_G - \varepsilon$ for all $\varepsilon$, so $\mathfrak{M} \ge K_G$.

Therefore $\mathfrak{M} = K_G$. The CHSH functional provides the specific lower bound $B_{\text{quant}}/B_{\text{class}} = \sqrt{2}$, confirming $K_G \ge \sqrt{2}$. ∎

Definition 4.3.3 (Operational Maakoul Constant). For a learning map $\Phi$ with fixed point set $\text{Fix}(\Phi)$,
\mathfrak{M}_{\text{ops}}(\Phi) = \sup_{\substack{\beta \\ \rho\in\text{Fix}(\Phi)}} \frac{|\beta(C_{\text{quant}}(\rho))|}{B_{\text{class}}(\beta)}.

Lemma 4.3.4. If the shared resource state $\rho$ has non‑zero quantum discord, then $\mathfrak{M}_{\text{ops}}(\Phi) > 1$.

4.4 Graph‑Structured Systems

Definition 4.4.1. For a graph $G=(V,E)$, $\mathfrak{M}(G)$ is the supremum of $\mathfrak{M}(\mathcal{A}_1,\dots,\mathcal{A}_n)$ over all choices of local algebras and all correlation tensors achievable under the communication constraints of $G$.

Proposition 4.4.2. If $G$ is a tree, $\mathfrak{M}(G)=1$. If $G$ contains a cycle, $\mathfrak{M}(G) \ge \sqrt{2}$ and can be as large as $K_G$ when $G$ is complete.

Proof. Trees admit classical hidden variable models (Fine’s theorem generalized to no‑signalling networks). Hence no Bell inequality violation is possible. For a cycle, the CHSH scenario can be embedded, giving $\mathfrak{M}(G)\ge\sqrt{2}$. For complete graphs, one can achieve the full Grothendieck bound. ∎

4.5 Multi‑Agent Learning Correlations and Protocols

Definition 4.5.1. Consider $n$ learning agents, each with a private algebra $\mathcal{A}_i$ and a public algebra $\mathcal{B}$. A learning protocol consists of:

1. Initial states $\rho_i$ on $\mathcal{A}_i$;
2. Communication channels $\Phi_{ij}: \mathcal{A}_j \to \mathcal{A}_i$;
3. A joint state $\omega$ on $\mathcal{A}_1 \otimes \cdots \otimes \mathcal{A}_n \otimes \mathcal{B}$ consistent with local updates.

Definition 4.5.2. The learning correlation set $\mathcal{L}_n(T)$ is the set of correlation tensors achievable by some learning protocol after $T$ rounds of communication.

Theorem 4.5.3 (Interpolation by Communication). For $T = 0$, $\mathcal{L}_n(0) = \mathcal{C}_{\text{class}}$. For $T \ge 1$, $\mathcal{C}_{\text{class}} \subsetneq \mathcal{L}_n(T) \subsetneq \mathcal{C}_{\text{quant}}$, with exact characterization depending on the communication topology. For complete graph communication, $\mathcal{L}_n(T) \to \mathcal{C}_{\text{quant}}$ as $T \to \infty$.

