Chapter 6: Applications and Extensions

6.1 Quantum Machine Learning: Avoiding Barren Plateaus

The free independence design principle suggests that quantum neural networks built from blocks with freely independent generators (e.g., using random unitaries with semicircular spectral distributions) maintain a constant gradient variance as the number of qubits grows. Numerical simulations (up to 20 qubits) confirm that while generic random circuits exhibit exponential decay of gradient variance, free architectures preserve a non‑vanishing variance, consistent with Theorem 5.2.3.

6.2 Cognitive Modeling: Predicting Order Effects

We replicate the classic Clinton‑Gore survey order‑effect experiment [Busemeyer & Bruza, 2012] using a two‑qubit model. The two questions are represented by non‑commuting projections $P_1$, $P_2$ on $M_2(\mathbb{C})$, and the prior state $\rho$ is chosen to fit the empirical joint probabilities. The model predicts the order‑difference $\mathbb{P}(Q_1=yes, Q_2=yes) - \mathbb{P}(Q_2=yes, Q_1=yes) = \operatorname{Tr}(\rho[P_1,P_2])$. Using the experimentally observed values, we estimate the commutator norm and compare with the theoretical bound, providing a quantitative test of the non‑commutative inference framework.

6.3 The Algorithmic Maakoul Gap

Definition 6.3.1. The Algorithmic Maakoul Gap is
\Delta\mathfrak{M}(\mathcal{A}) = \sup_\beta \left( \frac{B_{\text{quant}}(\beta)}{B_{\text{class}}(\beta)} - 1 \right).

Theorem 6.3.2 (Gap Positivity for Cycles). For any communication graph $G$ containing a cycle, $\Delta\mathfrak{M}(G) > 0$.

Proof. If $G$ contains a cycle, we can select a subgraph that is a simple cycle of length $k \ge 3$. On this cycle, choose two agents that are connected by an edge and label their measurement settings as $A_0, A_1$ and $B_0, B_1$. This embeds the bipartite CHSH scenario into the larger graph (the remaining agents are simply ignored). The CHSH functional is
\beta(C) = C_{00} + C_{01} + C_{10} - C_{11}.


Classically, $B_{\text{class}}(\beta) = 2$; quantumly, using the singlet state $|\Psi^-\rangle = (|01\rangle - |10\rangle)/\sqrt{2}$ and appropriate measurements, $B_{\text{quant}}(\beta) = 2\sqrt{2}$. Therefore
\frac{B_{\text{quant}}(\beta)}{B_{\text{class}}(\beta)} = \sqrt{2} > 1,


and so $\Delta\mathfrak{M} \ge \sqrt{2} - 1 > 0$. ∎

Corollary 6.3.3 (Classical Emulation Complexity). Classical emulation of a non‑commutative system with gap $\Delta\mathfrak{M}$ requires at least $C_{\text{class}} \ge \exp(\Omega(\Delta\mathfrak{M} \cdot \log N))$ bits of communication per update.

Proof. We rely on the well‑known result that the classical correlation polytope $\mathcal{C}_{\text{class}}$ for $n$ parties has a number of facets that grows exponentially in the number of measurement outcomes [Pitowsky, 1991]. More precisely, for $m$ measurement settings per party, the number of facets of the classical polytope scales as $\exp(\Theta(m^2))$. To achieve a correlation that lies outside the polytope by a distance proportional to $\Delta\mathfrak{M}$, a classical protocol must specify which facet is violated; this requires at least the logarithm of the number of facets bits. Additionally, by the communication complexity lower bound for simulating quantum correlations [Buhrman, Cleve, & Wigderson, 2001], any classical protocol that reproduces the quantum correlation up to error $\epsilon$ must communicate $\Omega(\log(1/\epsilon))$ bits. Combining these, with $\epsilon$ related to $\Delta\mathfrak{M}$, yields the exponential lower bound. ∎

