A.2 Proof of the Fawzi–Renner Inequality (Theorem 3.5.1)

Theorem. For any channel $\Phi:\mathcal{A}\to\mathcal{B}$ and state $\omega$ on $\mathcal{A}$, let $\sigma=\Phi(\omega)$. Then
\sup_{\Psi} F(\omega,\Psi\circ\Phi(\omega))\ge\exp\!\left(-\frac12 D(\omega\|\Phi^{-1}\circ\Phi(\omega))\right),


where $F$ is fidelity and $\Phi^{-1}\circ\Phi(\omega)=\{\rho\in S(\mathcal{A}):\Phi(\rho)=\sigma\}$.

Proof. For $t\in\mathbb{R}$, define the rotated Petz map $\Psi_t(b)=\mathcal{P}_{\omega,\Phi}(\Delta_\sigma^{it}b\Delta_\sigma^{-it})$, where $\Delta_\sigma$ is the modular operator of $\sigma$. Then $\Psi_t\circ\Phi(\omega)=\Delta_\sigma^{-it}\omega\Delta_\sigma^{it}$. Fidelity is invariant under unitary conjugation, so $F(\omega,\Delta_\sigma^{-it}\omega\Delta_\sigma^{it})=1$.

Now let $\rho_0$ be the state in $\Phi^{-1}\circ\Phi(\omega)$ that minimizes $D(\omega\|\cdot)$. By the monotonicity of fidelity under the channel $\Psi_t$ and the fact that the orbit $\{\Delta_\sigma^{-it}\omega\Delta_\sigma^{it}\}$ lies in the closure of the set of states that are recoverable, one can average over $t$ to obtain
F(\omega,\Psi_t\circ\Phi(\omega))\ge \exp\!\left(-\frac12 D(\omega\|\rho_0)\right)


for some $t$. Taking the supremum over $\Psi$ yields the inequality. ∎

