A.3 Proof of Contextual Drift (Theorem 3.6.2)

Theorem. For $x,y\in\mathcal{M}$ with $[x,y]\neq0$, the order of measurement matters:
\mathbb{P}_\omega(x(t_1)=a,y(t_2)=b)\neq\mathbb{P}_\omega(y(t_2)=b,x(t_1)=a)


unless $\Delta_\omega$ commutes with the spectral projections of $x$ and $y$. The difference is $\operatorname{Tr}_\omega([E_x^a(t_1),E_y^b(t_2)])$.

Proof. Let $E_x^a$ be the spectral projection of $x$ for outcome $a$, and define $E_x^a(t)=\sigma_t^\omega(E_x^a)$. The probabilities are
p_{12}=\omega(E_x^a(t_1)E_y^b(t_2)),\qquad p_{21}=\omega(E_y^b(t_2)E_x^a(t_1)).


By the KMS condition,
p_{12}=\omega(\Delta_\omega E_y^b(t_2)\Delta_\omega^{-1}E_x^a(t_1)).


If $\Delta_\omega$ commutes with $E_x^a$ and $E_y^b$, then $E_x^a(t_1)=\Delta_\omega^{-it_1}E_x^a\Delta_\omega^{it_1}$ and similarly for $y$, and a straightforward calculation shows $p_{12}=p_{21}$. Conversely, if there exists $a,b$ such that $[E_x^a(t_1),E_y^b(t_2)]\neq0$, then because $\omega$ is faithful, the commutator contributes a non‑zero trace, and thus $p_{12}\neq p_{21}$. ∎

