A.4 Proof of the Grothendieck Equality (Theorem 4.3.2)

Theorem. For $\mathcal{A}_1=M_d(\mathbb{C})$, $\mathcal{A}_2=M_d(\mathbb{C})$ ($d\ge2$), $\mathfrak{M}=K_G$, the complex Grothendieck constant.

Proof. For any matrix $\beta=(\beta_{ij})$, define
B_{\text{class}}(\beta)=\sup_{|a_i|,|b_j|\le1}\Bigl|\sum_{ij}\beta_{ij}a_i b_j\Bigr|,\qquad
B_{\text{quant}}(\beta)=\sup_{\|u_i\|,\|v_j\|\le1}\Bigl|\sum_{ij}\beta_{ij}\langle u_i,v_j\rangle\Bigr|.


Grothendieck’s inequality asserts that $B_{\text{quant}}(\beta)\le K_G B_{\text{class}}(\beta)$ for all $\beta$, and $K_G$ is the smallest such constant. Hence $\mathfrak{M}\le K_G$.

Conversely, for any $\varepsilon>0$, there exists a matrix $\beta$ such that $B_{\text{quant}}(\beta)>(K_G-\varepsilon)B_{\text{class}}(\beta)$. The supremum on the left is achieved for some unit vectors $u_i,v_j$; by embedding these vectors into a finite‑dimensional space of dimension at most the number of variables, and then into $M_d(\mathbb{C})$ with $d$ sufficiently large, we can realize the corresponding quantum correlation as $C_{ij}=\langle u_i,v_j\rangle$ using a suitable state and measurements. Therefore $\mathfrak{M}\ge K_G-\varepsilon$ for all $\varepsilon$, so $\mathfrak{M}\ge K_G$. Hence $\mathfrak{M}=K_G$. ∎

