A.5 Proof of Geodesic Convexity of Relative Entropy (Theorem 5.3.2)

Theorem. $D(\rho\|\sigma)$ is strictly geodesically convex with respect to the Fisher–Rao metric $g^{\text{FR}}$.

Proof. The Fisher–Rao metric is the Hessian of $D(\cdot\|\sigma)$ at $\rho=\sigma$. For a geodesic $\gamma(t)$ connecting $\rho_0$ to $\rho_1$, the second derivative satisfies
\frac{d^2}{dt^2}D(\gamma(t)\|\sigma)=g^{\text{FR}}_{\gamma(t)}(\dot\gamma,\dot\gamma)\ge0,


with equality only if $\dot\gamma=0$. This follows from the integral representation
D(\rho\|\sigma)=\int_0^\infty\operatorname{Tr}\bigl((\sigma-\rho)(s+\rho)^{-1}(\sigma-\rho)(s+\sigma)^{-1}\bigr)ds


and the convexity of the map $\rho\mapsto (s+\rho)^{-1}$ (Lieb’s concavity). ∎

