A.6 Proof of Exponential Convergence of Langevin Flow (Theorem 5.4.2)

Theorem. The non‑commutative Langevin flow converges exponentially to the Gibbs state $\rho_\infty=e^{-\beta V}/\tau(e^{-\beta V})$, minimizing the free energy $\mathcal{L}(\rho)=\tau(\rho V)-\beta^{-1}S(\rho)$.

Proof. The Lindblad generator $\mathcal{L}$ satisfies detailed balance with respect to $\rho_\infty$. The free energy evolves as
\frac{d}{dt}\mathcal{L}(\rho_t)=\operatorname{Tr}\bigl(V\frac{d\rho_t}{dt}\bigr)-\beta^{-1}\frac{d}{dt}S(\rho_t)
=-\beta^{-1}\sum_j\operatorname{Tr}\bigl(L_j\rho_t L_j^*(\log\rho_t-\log\rho_\infty)\bigr)\le0,


by Spohn’s inequality. Hence $\mathcal{L}(\rho_t)$ decreases monotonically, with equality only at $\rho_\infty$. The generator $\mathcal{L}$ has a spectral gap $\gamma>0$ because the associated Dirichlet form satisfies a Poincaré inequality (a consequence of the positive Ricci curvature, Theorem 5.3.3). Therefore $\mathcal{L}(\rho_t)-\mathcal{L}(\rho_\infty)\le e^{-\gamma t}(\mathcal{L}(\rho_0)-\mathcal{L}(\rho_\infty))$. ∎

