Appendix B: Background on von Neumann Algebras and Modular Theory

B.1 GNS Construction (Detailed)

Let $\mathcal{A}$ be a C*-algebra and $\omega$ a state. Define $\langle a,b\rangle_\omega=\omega(b^*a)$. This is a positive semi‑definite sesquilinear form. Set $N_\omega=\{a\in\mathcal{A}:\omega(a^*a)=0\}$. Then $\mathcal{A}/N_\omega$ is a pre‑Hilbert space; its completion is $H_\omega$. Define $\pi_\omega(a)(b+N_\omega)=ab+N_\omega$, extended continuously. Then $\pi_\omega$ is a *‑representation of $\mathcal{A}$ on $H_\omega$, and $\xi_\omega=1+N_\omega$ is cyclic: $\pi_\omega(\mathcal{A})\xi_\omega$ is dense. Moreover, $\omega(a)=\langle\xi_\omega,\pi_\omega(a)\xi_\omega\rangle$. If $\omega$ is faithful, $N_\omega=\{0\}$ and $\pi_\omega$ is faithful.

B.2 Tomita–Takesaki Theory

Let $\mathcal{M}\subseteq B(H)$ be a von Neumann algebra with a cyclic and separating vector $\Omega$. Define $S:a\Omega\mapsto a^*\Omega$ for $a\in\mathcal{M}$, extended to its closure. $S$ is antilinear and closable; its polar decomposition $S=J\Delta^{1/2}$ gives the modular conjugation $J$ (antilinear involution) and the modular operator $\Delta=S^*S$. The modular automorphism group is $\sigma_t(x)=\Delta^{it}x\Delta^{-it}$ for $x\in\mathcal{M}$. Properties:

· $\sigma_t$ is a one‑parameter automorphism group of $\mathcal{M}$;
· $J\mathcal{M}J=\mathcal{M}'$ (the commutant);
· The KMS condition: for any $x,y\in\mathcal{M}$, there exists a function $F_{x,y}(t)$ analytic on $\{0<\Im t<1\}$ and continuous on the closure such that $F_{x,y}(t)=\omega(x\sigma_t(y))$ and $F_{x,y}(t+i)=\omega(\sigma_t(y)x)$.

B.3 Conditional Expectations and Takesaki’s Theorem

Theorem (Takesaki, 1972). Let $\mathcal{N}\subseteq\mathcal{M}$ be an inclusion of von Neumann algebras and let $\omega$ be a faithful normal state on $\mathcal{M}$. There exists a normal faithful conditional expectation $\mathbb{E}:\mathcal{M}\to\mathcal{N}$ preserving $\omega$ if and only if $\mathcal{N}$ is invariant under the modular automorphism group $\sigma_t^\omega$.

This theorem is central to the Petz recovery condition.

