Appendix D: Tensor Network Representations for Non‑Commutative Inference

D.1 Matrix Product States (MPS)

For a 1D chain of $N$ sites with local dimension $d$, an MPS is
|\psi\rangle=\sum_{s_1,\dots,s_N}\operatorname{Tr}(A_1^{s_1}\cdots A_N^{s_N})|s_1\cdots s_N\rangle,


where each $A_i^{s}$ is a $D\times D$ matrix (bond dimension $D$). For mixed states, one uses matrix product density operators (MPDO) or purifications.

D.2 Efficient Computation of the Petz Map

Given a prior state $\rho$ as an MPS and a local channel $\Phi$ (e.g., a product of local CP maps), the Petz map $\mathcal{P}_{\omega,\Phi}$ can be approximated by variational methods. One solves a convex optimization over the space of MPS to invert the channel, typically using DMRG or TEBD algorithms. The cost scales as $O(ND^3)$ per update, allowing practical simulations for moderate $N$ when $D$ is bounded.

D.3 Complexity

For systems with limited entanglement (bond dimension bounded), the representation remains efficient. This connects the abstract operator‑algebraic theory to scalable numerical implementations.

