Appendix E: Navascués–Pironio–Acín (NPA) Hierarchy

E.1 Definition

Let $S$ be the set of measurement operators for $n$ parties. For each integer $k\ge1$, define $\mathcal{C}_{\text{quant}}^{(k)}$ as the set of correlation tensors $C$ for which there exists a positive semi‑definite moment matrix $\Gamma$ indexed by words of length at most $k$ in the measurement operators, satisfying $\Gamma_{1,1}=1$ and linear constraints that encode the correlation values. The sequence $\mathcal{C}_{\text{quant}}^{(k)}$ is decreasing and converges to $\mathcal{C}_{\text{quant}}$ from above.

E.2 SDP Formulation

For a given correlation tensor $C$, the feasibility problem at level $k$ is a semidefinite program:
\begin{aligned}
\text{find } &\Gamma\succeq0\\
\text{such that } &\Gamma_{1,1}=1,\\
&\Gamma_{w,w'}=\overline{\Gamma_{w',w}}\ \text{(symmetry)},\\
&C_{i_1\dots i_n}=\Gamma_{e,w_{i_1\dots i_n}},
\end{aligned}


where $w_{i_1\dots i_n}$ is the word representing the product of measurement operators in the order specified by the measurement settings.

E.3 Numerical Implementation

Using Python with cvxpy or cvxopt, these SDPs can be solved for small numbers of parties and measurement settings. For the CHSH scenario, level 1 already gives the Tsirelson bound $2\sqrt{2}$. Higher levels provide tighter approximations for more complex scenarios.

