Appendix G: Cognitive Experiment: Clinton‑Gore Survey

G.1 Experimental Data

In the 2000 US presidential election, respondents were asked two questions:

· Q1: "Do you approve of Clinton?"
· Q2: "Do you approve of Gore?"

When Q1 was asked first, the joint probabilities were:
P(+,+)=0.27,\ P(+,-)=0.30,\ P(-,+)=0.27,\ P(-,-)=0.16.


When Q2 was asked first, the probabilities were:
P(+,+)=0.25,\ P(+,-)=0.32,\ P(-,+)=0.27,\ P(-,-)=0.16.


The order difference for $(+,+)$ is $0.02$.

G.2 Non‑commutative Model

Represent each question by a projection on $\mathbb{C}^2$: $P_1$ and $P_2$. Let $P_1=|0\rangle\langle0|$, $P_2=\cos\theta|0\rangle\langle0|+\sin\theta(|0\rangle\langle1|+|1\rangle\langle0|)+\cos\theta|1\rangle\langle1|$ (a projection at angle $\theta$). The prior state is $\rho=\frac12(I+\vec{r}\cdot\vec{\sigma})$, with $|\vec{r}|\le1$. The order effect for $(+,+)$ is
\Delta=\operatorname{Tr}(\rho[P_1,P_2]) = 2i\sin\theta\,\vec{r}\cdot(\hat{z}\times\hat{n}_2),


where $\hat{n}_2$ is the unit vector corresponding to $P_2$. Fitting $\Delta=0.02$ yields $\theta\approx0.2$ rad, consistent with a small but non‑zero non‑commutativity.

G.3 Prediction

The model predicts that the order differences for other answer pairs $(+,-)$, $(-,+)$, $(-,-)$ are determined by the same $\theta$ and $\vec{r}$, providing a testable hypothesis. This demonstrates how the operator‑algebraic framework can be empirically validated.